1. How many services are running under port 1000?
  This appears to be a simple Nmap port scan question.
  nmap -p0-1000 [IP]
  should do it.
  Nmap is a tool that is most well-known for port scanning. It can identify open ports, the services running on them, and even the versions of those services. The -p part of the command tells Nmap which ports to scan specifically. Since we are working with ports under the number 1000, we want to search the ports up to that number. Then we just plug in the IP address that we intend to scan (given by TryHackMe itself), and badabing badaboom, we have an answer!

  Nmap scan report for [IP]
  Host is up (0.00057s latency).
  Not shown: 999 filtered ports
  PORT   STATE SERVICE
  21/tcp open  ftp
  80/tcp open  http

2. What is running on the higher port?
  This question wants to know what service is running on a port HIGHER than what we just found. Port numbers go up to 65535, so one option we can do is to just adjust our command to
  nmap -p1000-65535 [IP]
  this time and find the answer.
  Or, to make it a bit quicker, we can just try
  nmap -sV [IP]
  This will scan the *most common* 1,000 ports and report the versions of each service on the open ports. This gives us

  Nmap scan report for [IP]
  Host is up (0.00023s latency).
  Not shown: 997 filtered ports
  PORT     STATE SERVICE VERSION
  21/tcp   open  ftp     vsftpd 3.0.3
  80/tcp   open  http    Apache httpd 2.4.18 ((Ubuntu))
  2222/tcp open  ssh     OpenSSH 7.2p2 Ubuntu 4ubuntu2.8 (Ubuntu Linux; protocol 2.0)

